are you accountable for the things you say or the way you act when you are drunk i agree that being drunk is no excuse but at the same time you tend to say things you normally wouldn't say you may have always wanted to say them but when you have had a few you tend to get uh shall i say looser lips yes people are accountable for what they say and do even when they're drunk i'm not saying that you do this but many people use the excuse of being drunk to get away with things they don't have the guts to do when sober it should only take one time of being drunk stupid for someone to get the hint that they shouldn't drink so much next time how dumb would someone have to be to know that they do things they normally don't do and say things they normally don't say when they drink too much yet insist on getting drunk more times after the first time of finding out how you act when drunk you should control the amount of alcohol you swallow getting drunk doesn't give us a free get out of responsibility card Social rule Theory of conduct Alcoholics Anonymous Friends Trailer Park Boys Humphrey Bogart Shaggy dog story The nature of God in Western theology Theodicy Maison Ikkoku Poker jargon Minor Discworld concepts President (game) Rick Santorum Dilbert Hangover Nicomachean Ethics Cocaine Soft drink Criticism of libertarianism Similarities between the Bible and the Qur'an Alcoholic beverage Practices of Jehovah's Witnesses Avenue Q Co-Dependent's Day Samuel Goldwyn Homer Simpson Consensus decision-making Yerba mate Rape Rum Caffeine Eternal Sunshine of the Spotless Mind Sin City Knots Landing Mark 16 Customs and etiquette of Japan Fecal incontinence Futurama (TV series - season 2) David Hume Legalism (theology) Tooth Alcoholism Ocean's Twelve Book of Isaiah Stupid White Men The Catcher in the Rye Hiberno-English Plame affair Hide and Seek (Stargate Atlantis) Scenes from a Memory Mothers Against Drunk Driving Brian Griffin Jim Morrison Jumpstart 3rd Grade Sola fide Shit Ayyavazhi my